{"atom_id": "ig34_p0149_a016", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 149, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "TABLE_ROW", "verbatim": "| CEEDDY | Study Day of End of Event | Num | | Timing | Actual study day of end of the clinical event expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics. | Perm |", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0149_a017", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 149, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "TABLE_ROW", "verbatim": "| CESTRF | Start Relative to Reference Period | Char | (STNREF) | Timing | Describes the start of the observation as being before or after the reference time point and a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables. | Perm |", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": ["§4.4.7"], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0149_a018", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 149, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "TABLE_ROW", "verbatim": "| CEENRF | End Relative to Reference Period | Char | (STNREF) | Timing | Describes the end of the event relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables. | Perm |", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": ["§4.4.7"], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0149_a019", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 149, "page_region": "bottom", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "TABLE_ROW", "verbatim": "| CESTRPT | Start Relative to Reference Time Point | Char | (STNREF) | Timing | Identifies the start of the observation as being before or after the reference time point defined by variable CETRPT. Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables. | Perm |", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": ["§4.4.7"], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0150_a001", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 150, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "TABLE_ROW", "verbatim": "| CETRPT | Start Reference Time Point | Char | | Timing | Description of datetime in ISO 8601 character format of the sponsor-defined reference point referred to by --STRPT. Examples: \"2003-12-15\", \"VISIT 2\". | Perm |", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0150_a002", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 150, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "TABLE_ROW", "verbatim": "| CEENRPT | End Relative to Reference Time Point | Char | (STNREF) | Timing | Describes the end of the observation as being before or after the sponsor-defined reference time point defined by variable CEENTRPT. Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables. | Perm |", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": ["§4.4.7"], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0150_a003", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 150, "page_region": "top", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "TABLE_ROW", "verbatim": "| CEENTRPT | End Reference Time Point | Char | | Timing | Description of datetime in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by CEENTRPT. Examples: \"2003-12-25\", \"VISIT 2\". | Perm |", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0150_a004", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 150, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "In this column, an asterisk (*) indicates that the variable may be subject to controlled terminology. CDISC/NCI codelist values are enclosed in parentheses.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0150_a005", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 150, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "HEADING", "verbatim": "CE – Assumptions", "heading_level": 4, "sibling_index": 3, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0150_a006", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 150, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "1. The determination of events to be considered clinical events versus adverse events should be done carefully and with reference to regulatory guidelines or consultation with a regulatory review division. Events of clinical interest as defined by the protocol that are not considered AEs should be reflected as CEs.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0150_a007", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 150, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "(a) Events considered to be clinical events may include episodes of symptoms of the disease under study (often known as \"signs and symptoms\"), or events that do not constitute adverse events in themselves, though they might lead to the identification of an adverse event. For example, in a study of an investigational treatment for migraine headaches, migraine headaches may not be considered as adverse events per protocol. The occurrence of migraines or associated signs and symptoms might be reported in CE.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0150_a008", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 150, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "(b) In vaccine trials, certain adverse events may be considered to be signs of symptomatology and accordingly determined to be clinical events. If any event is considered serious, then the serious adverse event flag (--SER) and the serious adverse event flags (--SCAT, --SCOD, --SDTH, --SDHSP, --SLIFE, --SOD, --SMIE) would be required in the CE domain.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0150_a009", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 150, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "(c) Other studies might track the occurrence of specific events as efficacy endpoints. For example, in a study of an investigational treatment for prevention of ischemic stroke, all occurrences of TIA, stroke, and death might be captured as clinical events and assessed as to whether they meet endpoint criteria. Note that other information about these events may be reported in other datasets. For example, the event leading to death would be reported in AE; death would also be a record in the Disposition (DS) domain.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0150_a010", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 150, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.2.3 [Clinical Events (CE)]", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "2. CEOCCUR and CEPRESP are used together to indicate whether the event in CETERM was prespecified and whether it occurred. CEPRESP can be used to separate records that correspond to probing questions for prespecified events from those that represent spontaneously reported events, whereas CEOCCUR contains the responses to such questions. The following table shows how these variables are populated in various situations.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.2+R15", "ts": "2026-04-25T00:00:00Z"}}
